[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/eigen-c-library] Eigen is implemented using the expression templates metaprogramming technique, meaning it builds expression trees at compile time and generates custom code to evaluate these.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/eigen-c-library] Using expression templates and a cost model of floating point operations, the library performs its own loop unrolling and vectorization.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/eigen-c-library] Eigen itself can provide BLAS and a subset of LAPACK interfaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] and their representations in vector spaces and through matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is central to almost all areas of mathematics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For instance, linear algebra is fundamental in modern presentations of geometry, including for defining basic objects such as lines, planes and rotations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Also, functional analysis, a branch of mathematical analysis, may be viewed as the application of linear algebra to function spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is also used in most sciences and fields of engineering because it allows modeling many natural phenomena, and computing efficiently with such models.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For nonlinear systems, which cannot be modeled with linear algebra, it is often used for dealing with first-order approximations, using the fact that the differential of a multivariate function at a point is the linear map that best approximates the function near that point.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The procedure (using counting rods) for solving simultaneous linear equations now called Gaussian elimination appears in the ancient Chinese mathematical text Chapter Eight: *Rectangular Arrays* of *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Its use is illustrated in eighteen problems, with two to five equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Systems of linear equations arose in Europe with the introduction in 1637 by René Descartes of coordinates in geometry.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In fact, in this new geometry, now called Cartesian geometry, lines and planes are represented by linear equations, and computing their intersections amounts to solving systems of linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The first systematic methods for solving linear systems used determinants and were first considered by Leibniz in 1693.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In 1750, Gabriel Cramer used them for giving explicit solutions of linear systems, now called Cramer's rule.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Later, Gauss further described the method of elimination, which was initially listed as an advancement in geodesy.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In 1848, James Joseph Sylvester introduced the term *matrix*, which is Latin for *womb*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra grew with ideas noted in the complex plane.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For instance, two numbers w and z in $\mathbb {C}$ have a difference *w* – *z*, and the line segments *wz* and 0(*w* − *z*) are of the same length and direction.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The four-dimensional system $\mathbb {H}$ of quaternions was discovered by W.R.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The term *vector* was introduced as **v** = *x***i** + *y***j** + *z***k** representing a point in space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The quaternion difference *p* – *q* also produces a segment equipollent to *pq*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Other hypercomplex number systems also used the idea of a linear space with a basis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Arthur Cayley introduced matrix multiplication and the inverse matrix in 1856, making possible the general linear group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The mechanism of group representation became available for describing complex and hypercomplex numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Crucially, Cayley used a single letter to denote a matrix, thus treating a matrix as an aggregate object.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] He also realized the connection between matrices and determinants and wrote "There would be many things to say about this theory of matrices which should, it seems to me, precede the theory of determinants".
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Benjamin Peirce published his *Linear Associative Algebra* (1872), and his son Charles Sanders Peirce extended the work later.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The telegraph required an explanatory system, and the 1873 publication by James Clerk Maxwell of *A Treatise on Electricity and Magnetism* instituted a field theory of forces and required differential geometry for expression.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is flat differential geometry and serves in tangent spaces to manifolds.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Electromagnetic symmetries of spacetime are expressed by the Lorentz transformations, and much of the history of linear algebra is the history of Lorentz transformations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The first modern and more precise definition of a vector space was introduced by Peano in 1888; by 1900, a theory of linear transformations of finite-dimensional vector spaces had emerged.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra took its modern form in the first half of the twentieth century when many ideas and methods of previous centuries were generalized as abstract algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The development of computers led to increased research in efficient algorithms for Gaussian elimination and matrix decompositions, and linear algebra became an essential tool for modeling and simulations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Until the 19th century, linear algebra was introduced through systems of linear equations and matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In modern mathematics, the presentation through *vector spaces* is generally preferred, since it is more synthetic, more general (not limited to the finite-dimensional case), and conceptually simpler, although more abstract.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A vector space over a field *F* (often the field of the real numbers or of the complex numbers) is a set *V* equipped with two binary operations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Elements of *V* are called *vectors*, and elements of *F* are called *scalars*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The first operation, *vector addition*, takes any two vectors **v** and **w** and outputs a third vector **v** + **w**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The second operation, *scalar multiplication*, takes any scalar *a* and any vector **v** and outputs a new vector *a***v**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The axioms that addition and scalar multiplication must satisfy are the following.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The first four axioms mean that *V* is an abelian group under addition.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The elements of a specific vector space may have various natures; for example, they could be tuples, sequences, functions, polynomials, or matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is concerned with the properties of such objects that are common to all vector spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] for any vectors **u**,**v** in *V* and scalar *a* in F.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] for any vectors **u**, **v** in *V* and scalars *a*, *b* in F.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] When *V* = *W* are the same vector space, a linear map *T* : *V* → *V* is also known as a *linear operator* on V.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A bijective linear map between two vector spaces (that is, every vector from the second space is associated with exactly one in the first) is an isomorphism.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Because an isomorphism preserves linear structure, two isomorphic vector spaces are "essentially the same" from the linear algebra point of view, in the sense that they cannot be distinguished by using vector space properties.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] An essential question in linear algebra is testing whether a linear map is an isomorphism or not, and, if it is not an isomorphism, finding its range (or image) and the set of elements that are mapped to the zero vector, called the kernel of the map.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] All these questions can be solved by using Gaussian elimination or some variant of this algorithm.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The study of those subsets of vector spaces that are in themselves vector spaces under the induced operations is fundamental, similarly as for many mathematical structures.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] These subsets are called linear subspaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] More precisely, a linear subspace of a vector space V over a field F is a subset W of V such that **u** + **v** and *a***u** are in W, for every **u**, **v** in W, and every a in F.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For example, given a linear map *T* : *V* → *W*, the image *T*(*V*) of V, and the inverse image *T*−1(**0**) of **0** (called kernel or null space), are linear subspaces of W and V, respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The span of S is also the intersection of all linear subspaces containing S.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In other words, it is the smallest (for the inclusion relation) linear subspace containing S.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A set of vectors is linearly independent if none is in the span of the others.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Equivalently, a set S of vectors is linearly independent if the only way to express the zero vector as a linear combination of elements of S is to take zero for every coefficient ai.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A set of vectors that spans a vector space is called a spanning set or generating set.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If a spanning set S is *linearly dependent* (that is not linearly independent), then some element **w** of S is in the span of the other elements of S, and the span would remain the same if one were to remove **w** from S.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] One may continue to remove elements of S until getting a *linearly independent spanning set*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Such a linearly independent set that spans a vector space V is called a basis of *V*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The importance of bases lies in the fact that they are simultaneously minimal-generating sets and maximal independent sets.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] More precisely, if S is a linearly independent set, and T is a spanning set such that *S* ⊆ *T*, then there is a basis B such that *S* ⊆ *B* ⊆ *T*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Any two bases of a vector space *V* have the same cardinality, which is called the dimension of *V*; this is the dimension theorem for vector spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Moreover, two vector spaces over the same field F are isomorphic if and only if they have the same dimension.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If any basis of *V* (and therefore every basis) has a finite number of elements, *V* is a *finite-dimensional vector space*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If *U* is a subspace of *V*, then dim *U* ≤ dim *V*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In the case where *V* is finite-dimensional, the equality of the dimensions implies *U* = *V*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Matrices allow explicit manipulation of finite-dimensional vector spaces and linear maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Their theory is thus an essential part of linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Let V be a finite-dimensional vector space over a field *F*, and (**v**1, **v**2, ..., **v***m*) be a basis of *V* (thus m is the dimension of *V*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] is a bijection from *Fm*, the set of the sequences of m elements of F, onto V.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This is an isomorphism of vector spaces, if *Fm* is equipped with its standard structure of vector space, where vector addition and scalar multiplication are done component by component.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If W is another finite dimensional vector space (possibly the same), with a basis (**w**1, ..., **w***n*), a linear map f from W to V is well defined by its values on the basis elements, that is (*f*(**w**1), ..., *f*(**w***n*)).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Thus, f is well represented by the list of the corresponding column matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It follows that the theory of finite-dimensional vector spaces and the theory of matrices are two different languages for expressing the same concepts.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Two matrices that encode the same linear transformation in different bases are called similar.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It can be proven that two matrices are similar if and only if one can transform one into the other by elementary row and column operations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For a matrix representing a linear map from W to V, the row operations correspond to change of bases in V and the column operations correspond to change of bases in W.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Every matrix is similar to an identity matrix possibly bordered by zero rows and zero columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In terms of vector spaces, this means that, for any linear map from W to V, there are bases such that a part of the basis of W is mapped bijectively on a part of the basis of V, and that the remaining basis elements of W, if any, are mapped to zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Gaussian elimination is the basic algorithm for finding these elementary operations, and proving these results.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A finite set of linear equations in a finite set of variables, for example, *x*1, *x*2, ..., *xn*, or *x*, *y*, ..., *z* is called a **system of linear equations** or a **linear system**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Systems of linear equations form a fundamental part of linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Historically, linear algebra and matrix theory have been developed for solving such systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In the modern presentation of linear algebra through vector spaces and matrices, many problems may be interpreted in terms of linear systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Let T be the linear transformation associated with the matrix M.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] that is an element of the preimage of v by T.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The solutions of (**S′**) are exactly the elements of the kernel of T or, equivalently, M.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] for putting it in reduced row echelon form.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] These row operations do not change the set of solutions of the system of equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If $m=n$ and the matrix A is invertible, then the system has the unique solution $\mathbf {x} =A^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It follows from this matrix interpretation of linear systems that the same methods can be applied for solving linear systems and for many operations on matrices and linear transformations, which include the computation of the ranks, kernels, matrix inverses.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A linear endomorphism is a linear map that maps a vector space V to itself.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If V has a basis of n elements, such an endomorphism is represented by a square matrix of size n.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] where *Sn* is the group of all permutations of n elements, σ is a permutation, and (−1)*σ* the parity of the permutation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A matrix is invertible if and only if the determinant is invertible (i.e., nonzero if the scalars belong to a field).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Cramer's rule is a closed-form expression, in terms of determinants, of the solution of a system of n linear equations in n unknowns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Cramer's rule is useful for reasoning about the solution, but, except for *n* = 2 or 3, it is rarely used for computing a solution, since Gaussian elimination is a faster algorithm.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The *determinant of an endomorphism* is the determinant of the matrix representing the endomorphism in terms of some ordered basis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This definition makes sense since this determinant is independent of the choice of the basis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If f is a linear endomorphism of a vector space V over a field F, an *eigenvector* of f is a nonzero vector v of V such that *f*(*v*) = *av* for some scalar a in F.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] As z is supposed to be nonzero, this means that *M* – *aI* is a singular matrix, and thus that its determinant det (*M* − *aI*) equals zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If V is of dimension n, this is a monic polynomial of degree n, called the characteristic polynomial of the matrix (or of the endomorphism), and there are, at most, n eigenvalues.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If a basis exists that consists only of eigenvectors, the matrix of f on this basis has a very simple structure: it is a diagonal matrix such that the entries on the main diagonal are eigenvalues, and the other entries are zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In this case, the endomorphism and the matrix are said to be diagonalizable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] More generally, an endomorphism and a matrix are also said diagonalizable, if they become diagonalizable after extending the field of scalars.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In this extended sense, if the characteristic polynomial is square-free, then the matrix is diagonalizable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A symmetric matrix is always diagonalizable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] (it cannot be diagonalizable since its square is the zero matrix, and the square of a nonzero diagonal matrix is never zero).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] When an endomorphism is not diagonalizable, there are bases on which it has a simple form, although not as simple as the diagonal form.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The Frobenius normal form does not need to extend the field of scalars and makes the characteristic polynomial immediately readable on the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The Jordan normal form requires to extension of the field of scalar for containing all eigenvalues and differs from the diagonal form only by some entries that are just above the main diagonal and are equal to 1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A linear form is a linear map from a vector space V over a field F to the field of scalars F, viewed as a vector space over itself.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Equipped by pointwise addition and multiplication by a scalar, the linear forms form a vector space, called the **dual space** of V, and usually denoted V* or V′.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] These linear maps form a basis of *V**, called the dual basis of **v**1, ..., **v***n*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This defines the canonical linear map from V into (*V**)*, the dual of V*, called the **double dual** or **bidual** of V.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This canonical map is an isomorphism if V is finite-dimensional, and this allows identifying V with its bidual.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] There is thus a complete symmetry between a finite-dimensional vector space and its dual.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For every linear form h on W, the composite function *h* ∘ *f* is a linear form on V.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] between the dual spaces, which is called the **dual** or the **transpose** of f.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If V and W are finite-dimensional, and M is the matrix of f in terms of some ordered bases, then the matrix of f* over the dual bases is the transpose *M*T of M, obtained by exchanging rows and columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Besides these basic concepts, linear algebra also studies vector spaces with additional structure, such as an inner product.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The inner product is an example of a bilinear form, and it gives the vector space a geometric structure by allowing for the definition of length and angles.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] and so we can call this quantity the cosine of the angle between the two vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] An orthonormal basis is a basis where all basis vectors have length 1 and are orthogonal to each other.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Given any finite-dimensional vector space, an orthonormal basis could be found by the Gram–Schmidt procedure.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The inner product facilitates the construction of many useful concepts.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] If *T* satisfies *TT** = *T*T*, we call *T* normal.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It turns out that normal matrices are precisely the matrices that have an orthonormal system of eigenvectors that span *V*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] There is a strong relationship between linear algebra and geometry, which started with the introduction by René Descartes, in 1637, of Cartesian coordinates.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In this new (at that time) geometry, now called Cartesian geometry, points are represented by Cartesian coordinates, which are sequences of three real numbers (in the case of the usual three-dimensional space).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The basic objects of geometry, which are lines and planes are represented by linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Thus, computing intersections of lines and planes amounts to solving systems of linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This was one of the main motivations for developing linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Most geometric transformation, such as translations, rotations, reflections, rigid motions, isometries, and projections transform lines into lines.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It follows that they can be defined, specified, and studied in terms of linear maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This is also the case of homographies and Möbius transformations when considered as transformations of a projective space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Until the end of the 19th century, geometric spaces were defined by axioms relating points, lines, and planes (synthetic geometry).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Around this date, it appeared that one may also define geometric spaces by constructions involving vector spaces (see, for example, Projective space and Affine space).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It has been shown that the two approaches are essentially equivalent.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In classical geometry, the involved vector spaces are vector spaces over the reals, but the constructions may be extended to vector spaces over any field, allowing considering geometry over arbitrary fields, including finite fields.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Presently, most textbooks introduce geometric spaces from linear algebra, and geometry is often presented, at the elementary level, as a subfield of linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is used in almost all areas of mathematics, thus making it relevant in almost all scientific domains that use mathematics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] These applications may be divided into several wide categories.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Functional analysis studies function spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] These are vector spaces with additional structure, such as Hilbert spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra is thus a fundamental part of functional analysis and its applications, which include, in particular, quantum mechanics (wave functions) and Fourier analysis (orthogonal basis).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Nearly all scientific computations involve linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Consequently, linear algebra algorithms have been highly optimized.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] BLAS and LAPACK are the best known implementations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For improving efficiency, some of them configure the algorithms automatically, at run time, to adapt them to the specificities of the computer (cache size, number of available cores, ...).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Since the 1960s there have been processors with specialized instructions for optimizing the operations of linear algebra, optional array processors under the control of a conventional processor, supercomputers designed for array processing and conventional processors augmented with vector registers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Some contemporary processors, typically graphics processing units (GPU), are designed with a matrix structure, for optimizing the operations of linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The modeling of ambient space is based on geometry.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Sciences concerned with this space use geometry widely.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This is the case with mechanics and robotics, for describing rigid body dynamics; geodesy for describing Earth shape; perspectivity, computer vision, and computer graphics, for describing the relationship between a scene and its plane representation; and many other scientific domains.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In all these applications, synthetic geometry is often used for general descriptions and a qualitative approach, but for the study of explicit situations, one must compute with coordinates.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This requires the heavy use of linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Most physical phenomena are modeled by partial differential equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] To solve them, one usually decomposes the space in which the solutions are searched into small, mutually interacting cells.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For linear systems this interaction involves linear functions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For nonlinear systems, this interaction is often approximated by linear functions.This is called a linear model or first-order approximation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear models are frequently used for complex nonlinear real-world systems because they make parametrization more manageable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In both cases, very large matrices are generally involved.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Weather forecasting (or more specifically, parametrization for atmospheric modeling) is a typical example of a real-world application, where the whole Earth atmosphere is divided into cells of, say, 100 km of width and 100 km of height.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebra, a branch of mathematics dealing with vector spaces and linear mappings between these spaces, plays a critical role in various engineering disciplines, including fluid mechanics, fluid dynamics, and thermal energy systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Its application in these fields is multifaceted and indispensable for solving complex problems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In fluid mechanics, linear algebra is integral to understanding and solving problems related to the behavior of fluids.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It assists in the modeling and simulation of fluid flow, providing essential tools for the analysis of fluid dynamics problems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For instance, linear algebraic techniques are used to solve systems of differential equations that describe fluid motion.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] These equations, often complex and non-linear, can be linearized using linear algebra methods, allowing for simpler solutions and analyses.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In the field of fluid dynamics, linear algebra finds its application in computational fluid dynamics (CFD), a branch that uses numerical analysis and data structures to solve and analyze problems involving fluid flows.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] CFD relies heavily on linear algebra for the computation of fluid flow and heat transfer in various applications.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For example, the Navier–Stokes equations, fundamental in fluid dynamics, are often solved using techniques derived from linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This includes the use of matrices and vectors to represent and manipulate fluid flow fields.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Furthermore, linear algebra plays a crucial role in thermal energy systems, particularly in power systems analysis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It is used to model and optimize the generation, transmission, and distribution of electric power.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Linear algebraic concepts such as matrix operations and eigenvalue problems are employed to enhance the efficiency, reliability, and economic performance of power systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The application of linear algebra in this context is vital for the design and operation of modern power systems, including renewable energy sources and smart grids.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Overall, the application of linear algebra in fluid mechanics, fluid dynamics, and thermal energy systems is an example of the profound interconnection between mathematics and engineering.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It provides engineers with the necessary tools to model, analyze, and solve complex problems in these domains, leading to advancements in technology and industry.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This section presents several related topics that do not appear generally in elementary textbooks on linear algebra but are commonly considered, in advanced mathematics, as parts of linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The existence of multiplicative inverses in fields is not involved in the axioms defining a vector space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] One may thus replace the field of scalars by a ring R, and this gives the structure called a **module** over R, or R-module.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The concepts of linear independence, span, basis, and linear maps (also called module homomorphisms) are defined for modules exactly as for vector spaces, with the essential difference that, if R is not a field, there are modules that do not have any basis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The modules that have a basis are the free modules, and those that are spanned by a finite set are the finitely generated modules.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Module homomorphisms between finitely generated free modules may be represented by matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The theory of matrices over a ring is similar to that of matrices over a field, except that determinants exist only if the ring is commutative, and that a square matrix over a commutative ring is invertible only if its determinant has a multiplicative inverse in the ring.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Vector spaces are completely characterized by their dimension (up to an isomorphism).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In general, there is not such a complete classification for modules, even if one restricts oneself to finitely generated modules.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] However, every module is a cokernel of a homomorphism of free modules.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Modules over the integers can be identified with abelian groups, since the multiplication by an integer may be identified as a repeated addition.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Most of the theory of abelian groups may be extended to modules over a principal ideal domain.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In particular, over a principal ideal domain, every submodule of a free module is free, and the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups may be extended straightforwardly to finitely generated modules over a principal ring.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] There are many rings for which there are algorithms for solving linear equations and systems of linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] However, these algorithms have generally a computational complexity that is much higher than similar algorithms over a field.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] For more details, see Linear equation over a ring.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] In multilinear algebra, one considers multivariable linear transformations, that is, mappings that are linear in each of several different variables.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] This line of inquiry naturally leads to the idea of the dual space, the vector space *V** consisting of linear maps *f* : *V* → *F* where *F* is the field of scalars.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Multilinear maps *T* : *Vn* → *F* can be described via tensor products of elements of *V**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Vector spaces that are not finite-dimensional often require additional structure to be tractable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A normed vector space is a vector space along with a function called a norm, which measures the "size" of elements.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The norm induces a metric, which measures the distance between elements, and induces a topology, which allows for a definition of continuous maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] The metric also allows for a definition of limits and completeness – a normed vector space that is complete is known as a Banach space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] A complete metric space along with the additional structure of an inner product (a conjugate symmetric sesquilinear form) is known as a Hilbert space, which is in some sense a particularly well-behaved Banach space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] Functional analysis is of particular importance to quantum mechanics, the theory of partial differential equations, digital signal processing, and electrical engineering.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/linear-algebra] It also provides the foundation and theoretical framework that underlies the Fourier transform and related methods.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **matrix** (pl.: **matrices**) is a rectangular array of numbers or other mathematical objects with elements or entries arranged in rows and columns, usually satisfying certain properties of addition and multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, ${\begin{bmatrix}1&9&-13\\20&5&-6\end{bmatrix}}$ denotes a matrix with two rows and three columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This is often referred to as a "two-by-three matrix", a 2 × 3 matrix, or a matrix of dimension 2 × 3.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In linear algebra, matrices are used as linear maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In geometry, matrices are used for geometric transformations (for example rotations) and coordinate changes.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In numerical analysis, many computational problems are solved by reducing them to a matrix computation, and this often involves computing with matrices of huge dimensions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are used in most areas of mathematics and scientific fields, either directly, or through their use in geometry and numerical analysis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix is a rectangular array of numbers (or other mathematical objects), called the "entries" of the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are subject to standard operations such as addition and multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Most commonly, a matrix over a field F is a rectangular array of elements of ⁠ F ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **real matrix** and a **complex matrix** are matrices whose entries are respectively real numbers or complex numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] More general types of entries are discussed below.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The numbers (or other objects) in the matrix are called its *entries* or its *elements*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The horizontal and vertical lines of entries in a matrix are respectively called *rows* and *columns*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The size of a matrix is defined by the number of rows and columns it contains.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] There is no limit to the number of rows and columns that a matrix (in the usual sense) can have as long as they are positive integers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with m rows and n columns is called an m × n matrix, or m-by-n matrix, where m and n are called its **dimensions**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the matrix ${\mathbf {A} }$ above is a 3 × 2 matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices with a single row are called *row matrices* or *row vectors*, and those with a single column are called *column matrices* or *column vectors*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with the same number of rows and columns is called a *square matrix*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix with an infinite number of rows or columns (or both) is called an *infinite matrix*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In some contexts, such as computer algebra programs, it is useful to consider a matrix with no rows or no columns, called an *empty matrix*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The specifics of symbolic matrix notation vary widely, with some prevailing trends.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices are usually symbolized using upper-case letters (such as ${\mathbf {A} }$ in the examples above), while the corresponding lower-case letters, with two subscript indices (e.g., ⁠ $a_{11}$ ⁠, or ⁠ $a_{1,1}$ ⁠), represent the entries.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In addition to using upper-case letters to symbolize matrices, many authors use a special typographical style, commonly boldface roman (non-italic), to further distinguish matrices from other mathematical objects.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An alternative notation involves the use of a double-underline with the variable name, with or without boldface style, as in ⁠ ${\underline {\underline {A}}}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entry in the *i*th row and *j*th column of a matrix **A** is sometimes referred to as the ${i,j}$ or $(i,j)$ entry of the matrix, and commonly denoted by $a_{i,j}$ or ⁠ $a_{ij}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Alternative notations for that entry are ${\mathbf {A} [i,j]}$ and ⁠ $\mathbf {A} _{i,j}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Sometimes, the entries of a matrix can be defined by a formula such as ⁠ $a_{i,j}=f(i,j)$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the matrix above is defined as ${\mathbf {A} }=[i-j]$ or ⁠ $\mathbf {A} =((i-j))$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If matrix size is m × n, the above-mentioned formula $f(i,j)$ is valid for any $i=1,\dots ,m$ and any ⁠ $j=1,\dots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This can be specified separately or indicated using m × n as a subscript.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some programming languages utilize doubly subscripted arrays (or arrays of arrays) to represent an {m-by-n matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some programming languages start the numbering of array indexes at zero, in which case the entries of an m × n matrix are indexed by $0\leq i\leq m-1$ and ⁠ $0\leq j\leq n-1$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This article follows the more common convention in mathematical writing where enumeration starts from 1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of all m-by-n real matrices is often denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(m,n)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{m\times n}(\mathbb {R} )$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of all m × n matrices over another field, or over a ring *R*, is similarly denoted ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(m,n,R)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{m\times n}(R)$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *m* = *n*, such as in the case of square matrices, one does not repeat the dimension: ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}(n,R)$ ⁠, or ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}_{n}(R)$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Often, ⁠ M ⁠, or ⁠ $\operatorname {Mat}$ ⁠, is used in place of ⁠ ${\mathcal {M}}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Several basic operations can be applied to matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Some, such as *transposition* and *submatrix* do not depend on the nature of the entries.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Others, such as *matrix addition*, *scalar multiplication*, *matrix multiplication*, and *row operations* involve operations on matrix entries and therefore require that matrix entries are numbers or belong to a field or a ring.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In this section, it is supposed that matrix entries belong to a fixed ring, which is typically a field of numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix addition and subtraction require matrices of a consistent size, and are calculated entrywise.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Familiar properties of numbers extend to these operations on matrices: for example, addition is commutative, that is, the matrix sum does not depend on the order of the summands: **A** + **B** = **B** + **A**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The transpose is compatible with addition and scalar multiplication, as expressed by (*c***A**)T = *c*(**A**T) and (**A** + **B**)T = **A**T + **B**T.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix multiplication satisfies the rules (**AB**)**C** = **A**(**BC**) (associativity), and (**A** + **B**)**C** = **AC** + **BC** as well as **C**(**A** + **B**) = **CA** + **CB** (left and right distributivity), whenever the size of the matrices is such that the various products are defined.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The product **AB** may be defined without **BA** being defined, namely if **A** and **B** are m × n and n × k matrices, respectively, and *m* ≠ *k*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In other words, matrix multiplication is not commutative, in marked contrast to (rational, real, or complex) numbers, whose product is independent of the order of the factors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Besides the ordinary matrix multiplication just described, other less frequently used operations on matrices that can be considered forms of multiplication also exist, such as the Hadamard product and the Kronecker product.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] They arise in solving matrix equations such as the Sylvester equation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] These operations are used in several ways, including solving linear equations and finding matrix inverses with Gauss elimination and Gauss–Jordan elimination, respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **submatrix** of a matrix is a matrix obtained by deleting any collection of rows or columns or both.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The minors and cofactors of a matrix are found by computing the determinant of certain submatrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A **principal submatrix** is a square submatrix obtained by removing certain rows and columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The definition varies from author to author.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] According to some authors, a principal submatrix is a submatrix in which the set of row indices that remain is the same as the set of column indices that remain.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Other authors define a principal submatrix as one in which the first k rows and columns, for some number k, are the ones that remain; this type of submatrix has also been called a **leading principal submatrix**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices can be used to compactly write and work with multiple linear equations, that is, systems of linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Using matrices, this can be solved more compactly than would be possible by writing out all the equations separately.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *n* = *m* and the equations are independent, then this can be done by writing $\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {A} ^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ where **A**−1 is the inverse matrix of **A**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **A** has no inverse, solutions—if any—can be found using its generalized inverse.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices and matrix multiplication reveal their essential features when related to *linear transformations*, also known as *linear maps*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The matrix **A** is said to represent the linear map f, and **A** is called the *transformation matrix* of f.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the 2 × 2 matrix $\mathbf {A} ={\begin{bmatrix}a&c\\b&d\end{bmatrix}}$ can be viewed as the transform of the unit square into a parallelogram with vertices at (0, 0), (*a*, *b*), (*a* + *c*, *b* + *d*), and (*c*, *d*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] These vectors define the vertices of the unit square.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The following table shows several 2 × 2 real matrices with the associated linear maps of ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The blue original is mapped to the green grid and shapes.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The origin (0, 0) is marked with a black point.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The last equality follows from the above-mentioned associativity of matrix multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The rank of a matrix **A** is the maximum number of linearly independent row vectors of the matrix, which is the same as the maximum number of linearly independent column vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Equivalently it is the dimension of the image of the linear map represented by **A**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The rank–nullity theorem states that the dimension of the kernel of a matrix plus the rank equals the number of columns of the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix is a matrix with the same number of rows and columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An n-by-n matrix is known as a square matrix of order n.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Any two square matrices of the same order can be added and multiplied.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entries aii form the main diagonal of a square matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] They lie on the imaginary line running from the top left corner to the bottom right corner of the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Square matrices of a given dimension form a noncommutative ring, which is one of the most common examples of a noncommutative ring.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If all entries of **A** below the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called an *upper triangular matrix*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Similarly, if all entries of **A** above the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called a *lower triangular matrix*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If all entries outside the main diagonal are zero, **A** is called a diagonal matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is called an identity matrix because multiplication with it leaves a matrix unchanged: ${\mathbf {AI}}_{n}={\mathbf {I}}_{m}{\mathbf {A}}={\mathbf {A}}$ for any m-by-n matrix **A**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A scalar multiple of an identity matrix is called a *scalar* matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix **A** that is equal to its transpose, that is, **A** = **A**T, is a symmetric matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If instead, **A** is equal to the negative of its transpose, that is, **A** = −**A**T, then **A** is a skew-symmetric matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In complex matrices, symmetry is often replaced by the concept of Hermitian matrices, which satisfies **A**∗ = **A**, where the star or asterisk denotes the conjugate transpose of the matrix, that is, the transpose of the complex conjugate of **A**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] By the spectral theorem, real symmetric matrices and complex Hermitian matrices have an eigenbasis; that is, every vector is expressible as a linear combination of eigenvectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In both cases, all eigenvalues are real.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This theorem can be generalized to infinite-dimensional situations related to matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A square matrix **A** is called *invertible* or *non-singular* if there exists a matrix **B** such that ${\mathbf {AB}}={\mathbf {BA}}={\mathbf {I}}_{n},$ where **I***n* is the n × n identity matrix with 1 for each entry on the main diagonal and 0 elsewhere.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **B** exists, it is unique and is called the *inverse matrix* of **A**, denoted **A**−1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are many algorithms for testing whether a square matrix is invertible, and, if it is, computing its inverse.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] One of the oldest, which is still in common use is Gaussian elimination.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A symmetric real matrix **A** is called *positive-definite* if the associated quadratic form $f({\mathbf {x}})={\mathbf {x}}^{\rm {T}}{\mathbf {Ax}}$ has a positive value for every nonzero vector **x** in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If *f*(**x**) yields only negative values then **A** is *negative-definite*; if f does produce both negative and positive values then **A** is *indefinite*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A symmetric matrix is positive-definite if and only if all its eigenvalues are positive, that is, the matrix is positive-semidefinite and it is invertible.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The table at the right shows two possibilities for 2-by-2 matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix are simply the entries along the diagonal, and so in these examples, the eigenvalues can be read directly from the matrices themselves.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The first matrix has two eigenvalues that are both positive, while the second has one that is positive and another that is negative.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In the case of complex matrices, the same terminology and results apply, with *symmetric matrix*, *quadratic form*, *bilinear form*, and *transpose* **x**T replaced respectively by Hermitian matrix, Hermitian form, sesquilinear form, and conjugate transpose **x**H.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An *orthogonal matrix* is a square matrix with real entries whose columns and rows are orthogonal unit vectors (that is, orthonormal vectors).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Equivalently, a matrix **A** is orthogonal if its transpose is equal to its inverse: $\mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }=\mathbf {A} ^{-1},\,$ which entails $\mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }\mathbf {A} =\mathbf {A} \mathbf {A} ^{\mathrm {T} }=\mathbf {I} _{n},$ where **I***n* is the identity matrix of size n.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of any orthogonal matrix is either +1 or −1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A *special orthogonal matrix* is an orthogonal matrix with determinant +1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The identity matrices have determinant 1 and are pure rotations by an angle zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The complex analog of an orthogonal matrix is a unitary matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The trace, tr(**A**) of a square matrix **A** is the sum of its diagonal entries.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The *determinant* of a square matrix **A** (denoted det(**A**) or |**A**|) is a number encoding certain properties of the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is nonzero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Its absolute value equals the area (in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ ⁠) or volume (in ⁠ $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ ⁠) of the image of the unit square (or cube), while its sign corresponds to the orientation of the corresponding linear map: the determinant is positive if and only if the orientation is preserved.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of 2 × 2 matrices is given by $\det {\begin{bmatrix}a&b\\c&d\end{bmatrix}}=ad-bc.$ The determinant of 3 × 3 matrices involves six terms (rule of Sarrus).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The more lengthy Leibniz formula generalizes these two formulae to all dimensions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Interchanging two rows or two columns affects the determinant by multiplying it by −1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Using these operations, any matrix can be transformed to a lower (or upper) triangular matrix, and for such matrices, the determinant equals the product of the entries on the main diagonal; this provides a method to calculate the determinant of any matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Finally, the Laplace expansion expresses the determinant in terms of minors, that is, determinants of smaller matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This expansion can be used for a recursive definition of determinants (taking as starting case the determinant of a 1 × 1 matrix, which is its unique entry, or even the determinant of a 0 × 0 matrix, which is 1), that can be seen to be equivalent to the Leibniz formula.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Determinants can be used to solve linear systems using Cramer's rule, where the division of the determinants of two related square matrices equates to the value of each of the system's variables.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A number ${\textstyle \lambda }$ and a nonzero vector **v** satisfying $\mathbf {A} \mathbf {v} =\lambda \mathbf {v}$ are called an *eigenvalue* and an *eigenvector* of **A**, respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Therefore the polynomial equation *p***A**(*λ*) = 0 has at most n different solutions, that is, eigenvalues of the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] They may be complex even if the entries of **A** are real.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] According to the Cayley–Hamilton theorem, *p***A**(**A**) = **0**, that is, the result of substituting the matrix itself into its characteristic polynomial yields the zero matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix calculations can be often performed with different techniques.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Many problems can be solved by both direct algorithms and iterative approaches.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the eigenvectors of a square matrix can be obtained by finding a sequence of vectors **x***n* converging to an eigenvector when n tends to infinity.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] To choose the most appropriate algorithm for each specific problem, it is important to determine both the effectiveness and precision of all the available algorithms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The domain studying these matters is called numerical linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] As with other numerical situations, two main aspects are the complexity of algorithms and their numerical stability.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Determining the complexity of an algorithm means finding upper bounds or estimates of how many elementary operations such as additions and multiplications of scalars are necessary to perform some algorithm, for example, multiplication of matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Calculating the matrix product of two n-by-n matrices using the definition given above needs *n*3 multiplications, since for any of the *n*2 entries of the product, n multiplications are necessary.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The Strassen algorithm outperforms this "naive" algorithm; it needs only *n*2.807 multiplications.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Theoretically faster but impractical matrix multiplication algorithms have been developed, as have speedups to this problem using parallel algorithms or distributed computation systems such as MapReduce.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In many practical situations, additional information about the matrices involved is known.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An important case concerns sparse matrices, that is, matrices whose entries are mostly zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are specifically adapted algorithms for, say, solving linear systems **Ax** = **b** for sparse matrices **A**, such as the conjugate gradient method.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An algorithm is, roughly speaking, numerically stable if little deviations in the input values do not lead to big deviations in the result.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, one can calculate the inverse of a matrix by computing its adjugate matrix: ${\mathbf {A}}^{-1}=\operatorname {adj} ({\mathbf {A}})/\det({\mathbf {A}}).$ However, this may lead to significant rounding errors if the determinant of the matrix is very small.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The norm of a matrix can be used to capture the conditioning of linear algebraic problems, such as computing a matrix's inverse.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] There are several methods to render matrices into a more easily accessible form.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] They are generally referred to as *matrix decomposition* or *matrix factorization* techniques.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] These techniques are of interest because they can make computations easier.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The LU decomposition factors matrices as a product of lower (**L**) and an upper triangular matrices (**U**).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Once this decomposition is calculated, linear systems can be solved more efficiently by a simple technique called forward and back substitution.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Likewise, inverses of triangular matrices are algorithmically easier to calculate.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The *Gaussian elimination* is a similar algorithm; it transforms any matrix to row echelon form.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Both methods proceed by multiplying the matrix by suitable elementary matrices, which correspond to permuting rows or columns and adding multiples of one row to another row.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Singular value decomposition (SVD) expresses any matrix **A** as a product **UDV**∗, where **U** and **V** are unitary matrices and **D** is a diagonal matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The eigendecomposition or *diagonalization* expresses **A** as a product **VDV**−1, where **D** is a diagonal matrix and **V** is a suitable invertible matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If **A** can be written in this form, it is called diagonalizable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This can be used to compute the matrix exponential *e***A**, a need frequently arising in solving linear differential equations, matrix logarithms and square roots of matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] To avoid numerically ill-conditioned situations, further algorithms such as the Schur decomposition can be employed.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices can be generalized in different ways.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Abstract algebra uses matrices with entries in more general fields or even rings, while linear algebra codifies properties of matrices in the notion of linear maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is possible to consider matrices with infinitely many columns and rows.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Another extension is tensors, which can be seen as higher-dimensional arrays of numbers, as opposed to vectors, which can often be realized as sequences of numbers, while matrices are rectangular or two-dimensional arrays of numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices, subject to certain requirements tend to form groups known as matrix groups.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Similarly under certain conditions matrices form rings known as matrix rings.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Though the product of matrices is not in general commutative, certain matrices form fields sometimes called matrix fields.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The objects of this category are natural numbers, representing the dimensions of the matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This article focuses on matrices whose entries are real or complex numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, matrices can be considered with much more general types of entries than real or complex numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] As a first step of generalization, any field, that is, a set where addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division operations are defined and well-behaved, may be used instead of ⁠ $\mathbb {R}$ ⁠ or ⁠ $\mathbb {C}$ ⁠, for example rational numbers or finite fields.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, coding theory makes use of matrices over finite fields.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Wherever eigenvalues are considered, as these are roots of a polynomial, they may exist only in a larger field than that of the entries of the matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For instance, they may be complex in the case of a matrix with real entries.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The possibility to reinterpret the entries of a matrix as elements of a larger field (for example, to view a real matrix as a complex matrix whose entries happen to be all real) then allows considering each square matrix to possess a full set of eigenvalues.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Alternatively one can consider only matrices with entries in an algebraically closed field, such as ⁠ $\mathbb {C} ,$ ⁠ from the outset.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices whose entries are polynomials, and more generally, matrices with entries in a ring R are widely used in mathematics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Rings are a more general notion than fields in that a division operation need not exist.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The very same addition and multiplication operations of matrices extend to this setting, too.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set M(*n*, *R*) (also denoted M*n*(R)) of all square n-by-n matrices over R is a ring called matrix ring, isomorphic to the endomorphism ring of the left R-module Rn.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] If the ring R is commutative, that is, its multiplication is commutative, then the ring M(*n*, *R*) is also an associative algebra over *R*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of square matrices over a commutative ring R can still be defined using the Leibniz formula; such a matrix is invertible if and only if its determinant is invertible in R, generalizing the situation over a field F, where every nonzero element is invertible.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices over superrings are called supermatrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices do not always have all their entries in the same ring – or even in any ring at all.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] One special but common case is block matrices, which may be considered as matrices whose entries themselves are matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The entries need not be square matrices, and thus need not be members of any ring; but in order to multiply them, their sizes must fulfill certain conditions: each pair of submatrices that are multiplied in forming the overall product must have compatible sizes.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Linear maps $\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ are equivalent to m-by-n matrices, as described above.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The matrix depends on the choice of the bases: different choices of bases give rise to different, but equivalent matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Many of the above concrete notions can be reinterpreted in this light, for example, the transpose matrix **A**T describes the transpose of the linear map given by **A**, concerning the dual bases.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] These properties can be restated more naturally: the category of matrices with entries in a field k with multiplication as composition is equivalent to the category of finite-dimensional vector spaces and linear maps over this field.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] More generally, the set of m × n matrices can be used to represent the R-linear maps between the free modules Rm and Rn for an arbitrary ring R with unity.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] When *n* = *m* composition of these maps is possible, and this gives rise to the matrix ring of n × n matrices representing the endomorphism ring of Rn.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A group is a mathematical structure consisting of a set of objects together with a binary operation, that is, an operation combining any two objects to a third, subject to certain requirements.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A group in which the objects are invertible ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices and the group operation is matrix multiplication is called a *matrix group* of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every such matrix group is a subgroup of (that is, a smaller group contained within) the group of *all* invertible ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices, the general linear group of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Any property of square matrices that is preserved under matrix products and inverses can be used to define a matrix group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the set of all ⁠ $n\times n$ ⁠ matrices whose determinant is 1 form a group called the special linear group of degree ⁠ n ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The set of orthogonal matrices, determined by the condition ${\mathbf {M}}^{\rm {T}}{\mathbf {M}}={\mathbf {I}},$ form the orthogonal group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every orthogonal matrix has determinant 1 or −1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Orthogonal matrices with determinant 1 form a group called the *special orthogonal group*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Every finite group is isomorphic to a matrix group, as one can see by considering the regular representation of the symmetric group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] General groups can be studied using matrix groups, which are comparatively well understood, using representation theory.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] It is also possible to consider matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The basic operations introduced above are defined the same way in this case.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrix multiplication, however, and all operations stemming therefrom are only meaningful when restricted to certain matrices, since the sum featuring in the above definition of the matrix product will contain an infinity of summands.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An easy way to circumvent this issue is to restrict to *finitary matrices* all of whose rows (or columns) contain only finitely many nonzero terms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] As in the finite case (see above), where matrices describe linear maps, infinite matrices can be used to describe operators on Hilbert spaces, where convergence and continuity questions arise.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, the explicit point of view of matrices tends to obfuscate the matter, and the abstract and more powerful tools of functional analysis are used instead, by relating matrices to linear maps (as in the finite case above), but imposing additional convergence and continuity constraints.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] An *empty matrix* is a matrix in which the number of rows or columns (or both) is zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Empty matrices can be a useful base case for certain recursive constructions, and can help to deal with maps involving the zero vector space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, if **A** is a 3 × 0 matrix and **B** is a 0 × 3 matrix, then **AB** is the 3 × 3 zero matrix corresponding to the null map from a 3-dimensional space V to itself, while **BA** is a 0 × 0 matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] There is no common notation for empty matrices, but most computer algebra systems allow creating and computing with them.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of the 0 × 0 matrix is conventionally defined to be 1, consistent with the empty product occurring in the Leibniz formula for the determinant.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] This value is also needed for consistency with the 2 × 2 case of the Desnanot–Jacobi identity relating determinants to the determinants of smaller matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] A semiring is similar to a ring, but elements need not have additive inverses, therefore one cannot do subtraction freely there.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The definition of addition and multiplication of matrices with entries in a ring applies to matrices with entries in a semiring without modification.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices of fixed size with entries in a semiring form a commutative monoid $\operatorname {Mat} (m,n;R)$ under addition.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Square matrices of fixed size with entries in a semiring form a semiring $\operatorname {Mat} (n;R)$ under addition and multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The determinant of an n × n square matrix M with entries in a commutative semiring R cannot be defined in general because the definition would involve additive inverses of semiring elements.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] where the sums are taken over even permutations and odd permutations, respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] Matrices and their multiplication can be defined with entries objects of a category equipped with a "tensor product" similar to multiplication in a ring, having coproducts similar to addition in a ring, in that the former is distributive over the latter.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] However, the multiplication thus defined may be only associative in a sense weaker than usual.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] These are part of a bigger structure called the *bicategory of matrices*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] The complete description of the above summary for interested readers follows.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] In general, the bicategory of matrices need not be a strict 2-category.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p01] For example, the composition of 1-morphisms may not be associative in the usual strict sense, but only up to coherent isomorphism.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] There are numerous applications of matrices, both in mathematics and other sciences.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Some of them merely take advantage of the compact representation of a set of numbers in a matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, text mining and automated thesaurus compilation makes use of document-term matrices such as tf-idf to track frequencies of certain words in several documents.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Complex numbers can be represented by particular real 2-by-2 matrices via $a+ib\leftrightarrow {\begin{bmatrix}a&-b\\b&a\end{bmatrix}},$ under which addition and multiplication of complex numbers and matrices correspond to each other.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, 2-by-2 rotation matrices represent the multiplication with some complex number of absolute value 1, as above.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] A similar interpretation is possible for quaternions and Clifford algebras in general.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] In game theory and economics, the payoff matrix encodes the payoff for two players, depending on which out of a given (finite) set of strategies the players choose.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The expected outcome of the game, when both players play mixed strategies, is obtained by multiplying this matrix on both sides by vectors representing the strategies.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The minimax theorem central to game theory is closely related to the duality theory of linear programs, which are often formulated in terms of matrix-vector products.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Early encryption techniques such as the Hill cipher also used matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] However, due to the linear nature of matrices, these codes are comparatively easy to break.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices over a polynomial ring are important in the study of control theory.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Chemistry makes use of matrices in various ways, particularly since the use of quantum theory to discuss molecular bonding and spectroscopy.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Examples are the overlap matrix and the Fock matrix used in solving the Roothaan equations to obtain the molecular orbitals of the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The adjacency matrix of a finite graph is a basic notion of graph theory.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] It records which vertices of the graph are connected by an edge.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices containing just two different values (1 and 0 meaning for example "yes" and "no", respectively) are called logical matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The distance (or cost) matrix contains information about the distances of the edges.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] These concepts can be applied to websites connected by hyperlinks, or cities connected by roads etc., in which case (unless the connection network is extremely dense) the matrices tend to be sparse, that is, contain few nonzero entries.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Therefore, specifically tailored matrix algorithms can be used in network theory.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] It encodes information about the local growth behavior of the function: given a critical point **x** = (*x*1, ..., *xn*), that is, a point where the first partial derivatives $\partial f/\partial x_{i}$ of f vanish, the function has a local minimum if the Hessian matrix is positive definite.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Quadratic programming can be used to find global minima or maxima of quadratic functions closely related to the ones attached to matrices (see above).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Another matrix frequently used in geometrical situations is the Jacobi matrix of a differentiable map ⁠ $f:\mathbb {R} ^{n}\to \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ ⁠.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Partial differential equations can be classified by considering the matrix of coefficients of the highest-order differential operators of the equation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] For elliptic partial differential equations this matrix is positive definite, which has a decisive influence on the set of possible solutions of the equation in question.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The finite element method is an important numerical method to solve partial differential equations, widely applied in simulating complex physical systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] It attempts to approximate the solution to some equation by piecewise linear functions, where the pieces are chosen concerning a sufficiently fine grid, which in turn can be recast as a matrix equation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Stochastic matrices are square matrices whose rows are probability vectors, that is, whose entries are non-negative and sum up to one.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Stochastic matrices are used to define Markov chains with finitely many states.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] A row of the stochastic matrix gives the probability distribution for the next position of some particle currently in the state that corresponds to the row.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Properties of the Markov chain—like absorbing states, that is, states that any particle attains eventually—can be read off the eigenvectors of the transition matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Statistics also makes use of matrices in many different forms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Descriptive statistics is concerned with describing data sets, which can often be represented as data matrices, which may then be subjected to dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The covariance matrix encodes the mutual variance of several random variables.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Random matrices are matrices whose entries are random numbers, subject to suitable probability distributions, such as matrix normal distribution.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Beyond probability theory, they are applied in domains ranging from number theory to physics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The first model of quantum mechanics (Heisenberg, 1925) used infinite-dimensional matrices to define the operators that took over the role of variables like position, momentum and energy from classical physics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] (This is sometimes referred to as matrix mechanics.) Matrices, both finite and infinite-dimensional, have since been employed for many purposes in quantum mechanics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] One particular example is the density matrix, a tool used in calculating the probabilities of the outcomes of measurements performed on physical systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Linear transformations and the associated symmetries play a key role in modern physics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, elementary particles in quantum field theory are classified as representations of the Lorentz group of special relativity and, more specifically, by their behavior under the spin group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Concrete representations involving the Pauli matrices and more general gamma matrices are an integral part of the physical description of fermions, which behave as spinors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Cabibbo–Kobayashi–Maskawa matrix, in turn, expresses the fact that the basic quark states that are important for weak interactions are not the same as, but linearly related to the basic quark states that define particles with specific and distinct masses.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The linear combination is given by a matrix known as the S-matrix, which encodes all information about the possible interactions between particles.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] A general application of matrices in physics is the description of linearly coupled harmonic systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The equations of motion of such systems can be described in matrix form, with a mass matrix multiplying a generalized velocity to give the kinetic term, and a force matrix multiplying a displacement vector to characterize the interactions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The best way to obtain solutions is to determine the system's eigenvectors, its normal modes, by diagonalizing the matrix equation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Techniques like this are crucial when it comes to the internal dynamics of molecules: the internal vibrations of systems consisting of mutually bound component atoms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] They are also needed for describing mechanical vibrations, and oscillations in electrical circuits.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Geometrical optics provides further matrix applications.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] In this approximative theory, the wave nature of light is neglected.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The result is a model in which light rays are indeed geometrical rays.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] There are two kinds of matrices, viz. a *refraction matrix* describing the refraction at a lens surface, and a *translation matrix*, describing the translation of the plane of reference to the next refracting surface, where another refraction matrix applies.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The optical system, consisting of a combination of lenses and reflective elements, is simply described by the matrix resulting from the product of the components' matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Jones calculus models the polarization of a light source as a $2\times 2$ vector, and the effects of optical filters on this polarization vector as a matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Matrices have a long history of application in solving linear equations but they were known as arrays until the 1800s.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Chinese text *The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art* written in the 10th–2nd century BCE is the first example of the use of array methods to solve simultaneous equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] In 1545 Italian mathematician Gerolamo Cardano introduced the method to Europe when he published *Ars Magna*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Japanese mathematician Seki used the same array methods to solve simultaneous equations in 1683.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The Dutch mathematicianJan de Witt represented transformations using arrays in his 1659 book *Elements of Curves* (1659).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Between 1700 and 1710 Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz publicized the use of arrays for recording information or solutions and experimented with over 50 different systems of arrays.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Arthur Cayley published a treatise on geometric transformations using matrices that were not rotated versions of the coefficients being investigated as had previously been done.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Instead, he defined operations such as addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division as transformations of those matrices and showed the associative and distributive properties held.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Cayley investigated and demonstrated the non-commutative property of matrix multiplication as well as the commutative property of matrix addition.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Early matrix theory had limited the use of arrays almost exclusively to determinants and Cayley's abstract matrix operations were revolutionary.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] He was instrumental in proposing a matrix concept independent of equation systems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] In 1858, Cayley published his *A memoir on the theory of matrices* in which he proposed and demonstrated the Cayley–Hamilton theorem.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The English mathematician Cuthbert Edmund Cullis was the first to use modern bracket notation for matrices in 1913 and he simultaneously demonstrated the first significant use of the notation **A** = [*a**i*,*j*] to represent a matrix where *a**i*,*j* refers to the ith row and the jth column.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The modern study of determinants sprang from several sources.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Number-theoretical problems led Gauss to relate coefficients of quadratic forms, that is, expressions such as *x*2 + *xy* − 2*y*2, and linear maps in three dimensions to matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Eisenstein further developed these notions, including the remark that, in modern parlance, matrix products are non-commutative.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] He also showed, in 1829, that the eigenvalues of symmetric matrices are real.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Jacobi studied "functional determinants"—later called Jacobi determinants by Sylvester—which can be used to describe geometric transformations at a local (or infinitesimal) level, see above.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Kronecker's *Vorlesungen über die Theorie der Determinanten* and Weierstrass's *Zur Determinantentheorie*, both published in 1903, first treated determinants axiomatically, as opposed to previous more concrete approaches such as the mentioned formula of Cauchy.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] At that point, determinants were firmly established.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Many theorems were first established for small matrices only, for example, the Cayley–Hamilton theorem was proved for 2 × 2 matrices by Cayley in the aforementioned memoir, and by Hamilton for 4 × 4 matrices.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Frobenius, working on bilinear forms, generalized the theorem to all dimensions (1898).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Also at the end of the 19th century, the Gauss–Jordan elimination (generalizing a special case now known as Gauss elimination) was established by Wilhelm Jordan.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] In the early 20th century, matrices attained a central role in linear algebra, partially due to their use in the classification of the hypercomplex number systems of the previous century.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The inception of matrix mechanics by Heisenberg, Born and Jordan led to studying matrices with infinitely many rows and columns.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Later, von Neumann carried out the mathematical formulation of quantum mechanics, by further developing functional analytic notions such as linear operators on Hilbert spaces, which, very roughly speaking, correspond to Euclidean space, but with an infinity of independent directions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] The word has been used in unusual ways by at least two authors of historical importance.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Bertrand Russell and Alfred North Whitehead in their *Principia Mathematica* (1910–1913) use the word "matrix" in the context of their axiom of reducibility.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] For example, a function Φ(*x*, *y*) of two variables x and y can be reduced to a *collection* of functions of a single variable, such as y, by "considering" the function for all possible values of "individuals" ai substituted in place of a variable x.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/matrix-mathematics-p02] Alfred Tarski in his 1941 *Introduction to Logic* used the word "matrix" synonymously with the notion of truth table as used in mathematical logic.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra aims to solve problems of continuous mathematics using finite precision computers, so its applications to the natural and social sciences are as vast as the applications of continuous mathematics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] It is often a fundamental part of engineering and computational science problems, such as image and signal processing, telecommunication, computational finance, materials science simulations, structural biology, data mining, bioinformatics, fluid dynamics, and computational statistics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Matrix methods are particularly used in finite difference methods, finite element methods, and the modeling of differential equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Noting the broad applications of numerical linear algebra, Lloyd N.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Trefethen and David Bau, III argue that it is "as fundamental to the mathematical sciences as calculus and differential equations", even though it is a comparatively small field.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Because many properties of matrices and vectors also apply to functions and operators, numerical linear algebra can also be viewed as a type of functional analysis which has a particular emphasis on practical algorithms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra's central concern with developing algorithms that do not introduce errors when applied to real data on a finite precision computer is often achieved by iterative methods rather than direct ones.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra was developed by computer pioneers like John von Neumann, Alan Turing, James H.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Wilkinson, Alston Scott Householder, George Forsythe, and Heinz Rutishauser, in order to apply the earliest computers to problems in continuous mathematics, such as ballistics problems and the solutions to systems of partial differential equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The first serious attempt to minimize computer error in the application of algorithms to real data is John von Neumann and Herman Goldstine's work in 1947.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The field has grown as technology has increasingly enabled researchers to solve complex problems on extremely large high-precision matrices, and some numerical algorithms have grown in prominence as technologies like parallel computing have made them practical approaches to scientific problems.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] For many problems in applied linear algebra, it is useful to adopt the perspective of a matrix as being a concatenation of column vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] For example, when solving the linear system $x=A^{-1}b$ , rather than understanding *x* as the product of $A^{-1}$ with *b*, it is helpful to think of *x* as the vector of coefficients in the linear expansion of *b* in the basis formed by the columns of *A*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Thinking of matrices as a concatenation of columns is also a practical approach for the purposes of matrix algorithms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] This is because matrix algorithms frequently contain two nested loops: one over the columns of a matrix *A*, and another over the rows of *A*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The singular value decomposition of a matrix $A^{m\times n}$ is $A=U\Sigma V^{\ast }$ where *U* and *V* are unitary, and $\Sigma$ is diagonal.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The diagonal entries of $\Sigma$ are called the singular values of *A*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Because singular values are the square roots of the eigenvalues of $AA^{\ast }$ , there is a tight connection between the singular value decomposition and eigenvalue decompositions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] This means that most methods for computing the singular value decomposition are similar to eigenvalue methods; perhaps the most common method involves Householder procedures.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The QR factorization of a matrix $A^{m\times n}$ is a matrix $Q^{m\times m}$ and a matrix $R^{m\times n}$ so that *A = QR*, where *Q* is orthogonal and *R* is upper triangular.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The two main algorithms for computing QR factorizations are the Gram–Schmidt process and the Householder transformation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The QR factorization is often used to solve linear least-squares problems, and eigenvalue problems (by way of the iterative QR algorithm).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] An LU factorization of a matrix *A* consists of a lower triangular matrix *L* and an upper triangular matrix *U* so that *A = LU*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The matrix *U* is found by an upper triangularization procedure which involves left-multiplying *A* by a series of matrices $M_{1},\ldots ,M_{n-1}$ to form the product $M_{n-1}\cdots M_{1}A=U$ , so that equivalently $L=M_{1}^{-1}\cdots M_{n-1}^{-1}$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The eigenvalue decomposition of a matrix $A^{m\times m}$ is $A=X\Lambda X^{-1}$ , where the columns of *X* are the eigenvectors of *A*, and $\Lambda$ is a diagonal matrix the diagonal entries of which are the corresponding eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] There is no direct method for finding the eigenvalue decomposition of an arbitrary matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Because it is not possible to write a program that finds the exact roots of an arbitrary polynomial in finite time, any general eigenvalue solver must necessarily be iterative.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Naive programs for Gaussian elimination are notoriously highly unstable, and produce huge errors when applied to matrices with many significant digits.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The simplest solution is to introduce pivoting, which produces a modified Gaussian elimination algorithm that is stable.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra characteristically approaches matrices as a concatenation of column vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] In order to solve the linear system $x=A^{-1}b$ , the traditional algebraic approach is to understand *x* as the product of $A^{-1}$ with *b*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Numerical linear algebra instead interprets *x* as the vector of coefficients of the linear expansion of *b* in the basis formed by the columns of *A*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Many different decompositions can be used to solve the linear problem, depending on the characteristics of the matrix *A* and the vectors *x* and *b*, which may make one factorization much easier to obtain than others.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] If *A* = *QR* is a QR factorization of *A*, then equivalently $Rx=Q^{\ast }b$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] This is as easy to compute as a matrix factorization.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] This is closely related to the solution to the linear system using the singular value decomposition, because singular values of a matrix are the absolute values of its eigenvalues, which are also equivalent to the square roots of the absolute values of the eigenvalues of the Gram matrix $X^{*}X$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] And if *A* = *LU* is an *LU* factorization of *A*, then *Ax* = *b* can be solved using the triangular matrices *Ly* = *b* and *Ux* = *y*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Matrix decompositions suggest a number of ways to solve the linear system *r* = *b* − *Ax* where we seek to minimize *r*, as in the regression problem.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The QR algorithm solves this problem by computing the reduced QR factorization of *A* and rearranging to obtain ${\widehat {R}}x={\widehat {Q}}^{\ast }b$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] This upper triangular system can then be solved for *x*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The SVD also suggests an algorithm for obtaining linear least squares.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] By computing the reduced SVD decomposition $A={\widehat {U}}{\widehat {\Sigma }}V^{\ast }$ and then computing the vector ${\widehat {U}}^{\ast }b$ , we reduce the least squares problem to a simple diagonal system.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] The fact that least squares solutions can be produced by the QR and SVD factorizations means that, in addition to the classical normal equations method for solving least squares problems, these problems can also be solved by methods that include the Gram-Schmidt algorithm and Householder methods.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Allow that a problem is a function $f:X\to Y$ , where *X* is a normed vector space of data and *Y* is a normed vector space of solutions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] For some data point $x\in X$ , the problem is said to be ill-conditioned if a small perturbation in *x* produces a large change in the value of *f*(*x*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Instability is the tendency of computer algorithms, which depend on floating-point arithmetic, to produce results that differ dramatically from the exact mathematical solution to a problem.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] When a matrix contains real data with many significant digits, many algorithms for solving problems like linear systems of equation or least squares optimisation may produce highly inaccurate results.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Creating stable algorithms for ill-conditioned problems is a central concern in numerical linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Some matrix decomposition methods may be unstable, but have straightforward modifications that make them stable; one example is the unstable Gram–Schmidt, which can easily be changed to produce the stable modified Gram–Schmidt.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Another classical problem in numerical linear algebra is the finding that Gaussian elimination is unstable, but becomes stable with the introduction of pivoting.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] There are two reasons that iterative algorithms are an important part of numerical linear algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] First, many important numerical problems have no direct solution; in order to find the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of an arbitrary matrix, we can only adopt an iterative approach.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Second, noniterative algorithms for an arbitrary $m\times m$ matrix require $O(m^{3})$ time, which is a surprisingly high floor given that matrices contain only $m^{2}$ numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Iterative approaches can take advantage of several features of some matrices to reduce this time.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] For example, when a matrix is sparse, an iterative algorithm can skip many of the steps that a direct approach would necessarily follow, even if they are redundant steps given a highly structured matrix.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] When *A* is symmetric and we wish to solve the linear problem *Ax* = *b*, the classical iterative approach is the conjugate gradient method.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] If *A* is not symmetric, then examples of iterative solutions to the linear problem are the generalized minimal residual method and CGN.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] If *A* is symmetric, then to solve the eigenvalue and eigenvector problem we can use the Lanczos algorithm, and if *A* is non-symmetric, then we can use Arnoldi iteration.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Several programming languages use numerical linear algebra optimisation techniques and are designed to implement numerical linear algebra algorithms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] These languages include MATLAB, Analytica, Maple, and Mathematica.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] Many numerical linear algebra commands in R rely on these more fundamental libraries like LAPACK.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/numerical-linear-algebra] More libraries can be found on the List of numerical libraries.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In mathematics, a **vector space** (also called a **linear space**) is a set whose elements, often called ***vectors***, can be added together and multiplied ("scaled") by numbers called *scalars*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The operations of vector addition and scalar multiplication must satisfy certain requirements, called *vector axioms*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] **Real vector spaces** and **complex vector spaces** are kinds of vector spaces based on different kinds of scalars: real numbers and complex numbers.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Scalars can also be, more generally, elements of any field.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Vector spaces generalize Euclidean vectors, which allow modeling of physical quantities (such as forces and velocity) that have not only a magnitude, but also a direction.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The concept of vector spaces is fundamental for linear algebra, together with the concept of matrices, which allows computing in vector spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This provides a concise and synthetic way for manipulating and studying systems of linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Vector spaces are characterized by their dimension, which, roughly speaking, specifies the number of independent directions in the space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This means that for two vector spaces over a given field and with the same dimension, the properties that depend only on the vector-space structure are exactly the same (that is, the vector spaces are isomorphic).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A vector space is *finite-dimensional* if its dimension is a natural number.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Otherwise, it is *infinite-dimensional*, and its dimension is an infinite cardinal.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Finite-dimensional vector spaces occur naturally in geometry and related areas.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Infinite-dimensional vector spaces occur in many areas of mathematics.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] For example, polynomial rings are countably infinite-dimensional vector spaces, and many function spaces have the cardinality of the continuum as a dimension.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Many vector spaces that are considered in mathematics are also endowed with other structures.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This is the case of algebras, which include field extensions, polynomial rings, associative algebras and Lie algebras.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This is also the case of topological vector spaces, which include function spaces, inner product spaces, normed spaces, Hilbert spaces and Banach spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In this article, vectors are represented in boldface to distinguish them from scalars.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A vector space over a field F is a non-empty set V together with a binary operation and a binary function that satisfy the eight axioms listed below.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In this context, the elements of V are commonly called *vectors*, and the elements of F are called *scalars*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] To have a vector space, the eight following axioms must be satisfied for every **u**, **v** and **w** in V, and a and b in F.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] When the scalar field is the real numbers, the vector space is called a *real vector space*, and when the scalar field is the complex numbers, the vector space is called a *complex vector space*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] These two cases are the most common ones, but vector spaces with scalars in an arbitrary field F are also commonly considered.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Such a vector space is called an F-*vector space* or a *vector space over F*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Specifically, the distributivity of scalar multiplication with respect to vector addition means that multiplication by a scalar *a* is an endomorphism of the group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The remaining three axioms establish that the function that maps a scalar *a* to the multiplication by *a* is a ring homomorphism from the field to the endomorphism ring of the group.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Even more concisely, a vector space is a module over a field.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] if and only if they have the same coefficients.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Also equivalently, they are linearly independent if a linear combination results in the zero vector if and only if all its coefficients are zero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A linear subspace is a vector space for the induced addition and scalar multiplication; this means that the closure property implies that the axioms of a vector space are satisfied.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] of linear subspaces is a linear subspace.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] if its elements are linearly independent and span the vector space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This is a fundamental property of vector spaces, which is detailed in the remainder of the section.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Consider a basis $(\mathbf {b} _{1},\mathbf {b} _{2},\ldots ,\mathbf {b} _{n})$ of a vector space V of dimension n over a field F.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The definition of a basis implies that every $\mathbf {v} \in V$ may be written $\mathbf {v} =a_{1}\mathbf {b} _{1}+\cdots +a_{n}\mathbf {b} _{n},$ with $a_{1},\dots ,a_{n}$ in F, and that this decomposition is unique.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The scalars $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}$ are called the *coordinates* of **v** on the basis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] They are also said to be the *coefficients* of the decomposition of **v** on the basis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] One also says that the n-tuple of the coordinates is the coordinate vector of **v** on the basis, since the set $F^{n}$ of the n-tuples of elements of F is a vector space for componentwise addition and scalar multiplication, whose dimension is n.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The one-to-one correspondence between vectors and their coordinate vectors maps vector addition to vector addition and scalar multiplication to scalar multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] It is thus a vector space isomorphism, which allows translating reasonings and computations on vectors into reasonings and computations on their coordinates.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Vector spaces stem from affine geometry, via the introduction of coordinates in the plane or three-dimensional space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Around 1636, French mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat founded analytic geometry by identifying solutions to an equation of two variables with points on a plane curve.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] To achieve geometric solutions without using coordinates, Bolzano introduced, in 1804, certain operations on points, lines, and planes, which are predecessors of vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Möbius (1827) introduced the notion of barycentric coordinates.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Bellavitis (1833) introduced an equivalence relation on directed line segments that share the same length and direction which he called equipollence.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A Euclidean vector is then an equivalence class of that relation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Vectors were reconsidered with the presentation of complex numbers by Argand and Hamilton and the inception of quaternions by the latter.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] They are elements in **R**2 and **R**4; treating them using linear combinations goes back to Laguerre in 1867, who also defined systems of linear equations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In 1857, Cayley introduced the matrix notation which allows for harmonization and simplification of linear maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Around the same time, Grassmann studied the barycentric calculus initiated by Möbius.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] He envisaged sets of abstract objects endowed with operations.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In his work, the concepts of linear independence and dimension, as well as scalar products are present.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Grassmann's 1844 work exceeds the framework of vector spaces as well since his considering multiplication led him to what are today called algebras.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Italian mathematician Peano was the first to give the modern definition of vector spaces and linear maps in 1888, although he called them "linear systems".
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Peano's axiomatization allowed for vector spaces with infinite dimension, but Peano did not develop that theory further.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In 1897, Salvatore Pincherle adopted Peano's axioms and made initial inroads into the theory of infinite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] An important development of vector spaces is due to the construction of function spaces by Henri Lebesgue.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This was later formalized by Banach and Hilbert, around 1920.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] At that time, algebra and the new field of functional analysis began to interact, notably with key concepts such as spaces of *p*-integrable functions and Hilbert spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The first example of a vector space consists of arrows in a fixed plane, starting at one fixed point.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This is used in physics to describe forces or velocities.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Given any two such arrows, **v** and **w**, the parallelogram spanned by these two arrows contains one diagonal arrow that starts at the origin, too.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This new arrow is called the *sum* of the two arrows, and is denoted **v** + **w**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In the special case of two arrows on the same line, their sum is the arrow on this line whose length is the sum or the difference of the lengths, depending on whether the arrows have the same direction.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Another operation that can be done with arrows is scaling: given any positive real number *a*, the arrow that has the same direction as **v**, but is dilated or shrunk by multiplying its length by *a*, is called *multiplication* of **v** by *a*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] When *a* is negative, *a***v** is defined as the arrow pointing in the opposite direction instead.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The following shows a few examples: if *a* = 2, the resulting vector *a***w** has the same direction as **w**, but is stretched to the double length of **w** (the second image).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Moreover, (−1)**v** = −**v** has the opposite direction and the same length as **v** (blue vector pointing down in the second image).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A second key example of a vector space is provided by pairs of real numbers x and y.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The order of the components x and y is significant, so such a pair is also called an ordered pair.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The first example above reduces to this example if an arrow is represented by a pair of Cartesian coordinates of its endpoint.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The simplest example of a vector space over a field *F* is the field *F* itself with its addition viewed as vector addition and its multiplication viewed as scalar multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] More generally, all *n*-tuples (sequences of length *n*) $(a_{1},a_{2},\dots ,a_{n})$ of elements *a**i* of *F* form a vector space that is usually denoted *F**n* and called a **coordinate space**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The case *n* = 1 is the above-mentioned simplest example, in which the field *F* is also regarded as a vector space over itself.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The case *F* = **R** and *n* = 2 (so **R**2) reduces to the previous example.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The various axioms of a vector space follow from the fact that the same rules hold for complex number arithmetic.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] More generally, field extensions provide another class of examples of vector spaces, particularly in algebra and algebraic number theory: a field *F* containing a smaller field *E* is an *E*-vector space, by the given multiplication and addition operations of *F*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] For example, the complex numbers are a vector space over **R**, and the field extension $\mathbf {Q} (i{\sqrt {5}})$ is a vector space over **Q**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Functions from any fixed set Ω to a field *F* also form vector spaces, by performing addition and scalar multiplication pointwise.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] That is, the sum of two functions *f* and *g* is the function $(f+g)$ given by $(f+g)(w)=f(w)+g(w),$ and similarly for multiplication.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Such function spaces occur in many geometric situations, when Ω is the real line or an interval, or other subsets of **R**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Many notions in topology and analysis, such as continuity, integrability or differentiability are well-behaved with respect to linearity: sums and scalar multiples of functions possessing such a property still have that property.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Therefore, the set of such functions are vector spaces, whose study belongs to functional analysis.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Systems of homogeneous linear equations are closely tied to vector spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] where $A={\begin{bmatrix}1&3&1\\4&2&2\end{bmatrix}}$ is the matrix containing the coefficients of the given equations, $\mathbf {x}$ is the vector $(a,b,c),$ $A\mathbf {x}$ denotes the matrix product, and $\mathbf {0} =(0,0)$ is the zero vector.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In a similar vein, the solutions of homogeneous *linear differential equations* form vector spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] yields $f(x)=ae^{-x}+bxe^{-x},$ where a and b are arbitrary constants, and $e^{x}$ is the natural exponential function.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The relation of two vector spaces can be expressed by *linear map* or *linear transformation*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] An *isomorphism* is a linear map *f* : *V* → *W* such that there exists an inverse map *g* : *W* → *V*, which is a map such that the two possible compositions *f* ∘ *g* : *W* → *W* and *g* ∘ *f* : *V* → *V* are identity maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Equivalently, *f* is both one-to-one (injective) and onto (surjective).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] If there exists an isomorphism between *V* and *W*, the two spaces are said to be *isomorphic*; they are then essentially identical as vector spaces, since all identities holding in *V* are, via *f*, transported to similar ones in *W*, and vice versa via *g*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Conversely, given a pair (*x*, *y*), the arrow going by *x* to the right (or to the left, if *x* is negative), and *y* up (down, if *y* is negative) turns back the arrow **v**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Linear maps *V* → *W* between two vector spaces form a vector space Hom*F*(*V*, *W*), also denoted L(*V*, *W*), or 𝓛(*V*, *W*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The space of linear maps from *V* to *F* is called the *dual vector space*, denoted *V*∗.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Via the injective natural map *V* → *V*∗∗, any vector space can be embedded into its *bidual*; the map is an isomorphism if and only if the space is finite-dimensional.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Once a basis of *V* is chosen, linear maps *f* : *V* → *W* are completely determined by specifying the images of the basis vectors, because any element of *V* is expressed uniquely as a linear combination of them.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] If dim *V* = dim *W*, a 1-to-1 correspondence between fixed bases of *V* and *W* gives rise to a linear map that maps any basis element of *V* to the corresponding basis element of *W*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] It is an isomorphism, by its very definition.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Therefore, two vector spaces over a given field are isomorphic if their dimensions agree and vice versa.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Another way to express this is that any vector space over a given field is *completely classified* (up to isomorphism) by its dimension, a single number.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In particular, any *n*-dimensional *F*-vector space *V* is isomorphic to *F**n*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] However, there is no "canonical" or preferred isomorphism; an isomorphism *φ* : *F**n* → *V* is equivalent to the choice of a basis of *V*, by mapping the standard basis of *F**n* to *V*, via *φ*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Moreover, after choosing bases of *V* and *W*, *any* linear map *f* : *V* → *W* is uniquely represented by a matrix via this assignment.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The determinant det (*A*) of a square matrix *A* is a scalar that tells whether the associated map is an isomorphism or not: to be so it is sufficient and necessary that the determinant is nonzero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The linear transformation of **R***n* corresponding to a real *n*-by-*n* matrix is orientation preserving if and only if its determinant is positive.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Endomorphisms, linear maps *f* : *V* → *V*, are particularly important since in this case vectors **v** can be compared with their image under *f*, *f*(**v**).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Any nonzero vector **v** satisfying *λ***v** = *f*(**v**), where *λ* is a scalar, is called an *eigenvector* of *f* with *eigenvalue* *λ*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Equivalently, **v** is an element of the kernel of the difference *f* − *λ* · Id (where Id is the identity map *V* → *V*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] If the field *F* is large enough to contain a zero of this polynomial (which automatically happens for *F* algebraically closed, such as *F* = **C**) any linear map has at least one eigenvector.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The vector space *V* may or may not possess an eigenbasis, a basis consisting of eigenvectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This phenomenon is governed by the Jordan canonical form of the map.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The set of all eigenvectors corresponding to a particular eigenvalue of *f* forms a vector space known as the *eigenspace* corresponding to the eigenvalue (and *f*) in question.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In addition to the above concrete examples, there are a number of standard linear algebraic constructions that yield vector spaces related to given ones.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A nonempty subset W of a vector space V that is closed under addition and scalar multiplication (and therefore contains the $\mathbf {0}$ -vector of V ) is called a *linear subspace* of V , or simply a *subspace* of V , when the ambient space is unambiguously a vector space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Subspaces of V are vector spaces (over the same field) in their own right.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The intersection of all subspaces containing a given set S of vectors is called its span, and it is the smallest subspace of V containing the set S .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Expressed in terms of elements, the span is the subspace consisting of all the linear combinations of elements of S .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Linear subspace of dimension 1 and 2 are referred to as a *line* (also *vector line*), and a *plane* respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] If *W* is an *n*-dimensional vector space, any subspace of dimension 1 less, i.e., of dimension $n-1$ is called a *hyperplane*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The counterpart to subspaces are *quotient vector spaces*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Given any subspace $W\subseteq V$ , the quotient space $V/W$ (" V modulo W ") is defined as follows: as a set, it consists of $\mathbf {v} +W=\{\mathbf {v} +\mathbf {w} :\mathbf {w} \in W\},$ where $\mathbf {v}$ is an arbitrary vector in V .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The sum of two such elements $\mathbf {v} _{1}+W$ and $\mathbf {v} _{2}+W$ is $\left(\mathbf {v} _{1}+\mathbf {v} _{2}\right)+W$ , and scalar multiplication is given by $a\cdot (\mathbf {v} +W)=(a\cdot \mathbf {v} )+W$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The key point in this definition is that $\mathbf {v} _{1}+W=\mathbf {v} _{2}+W$ if and only if the difference of $\mathbf {v} _{1}$ and $\mathbf {v} _{2}$ lies in W .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] This way, the quotient space "forgets" information that is contained in the subspace W .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The kernel $\ker(f)$ of a linear map $f:V\to W$ consists of vectors $\mathbf {v}$ that are mapped to $\mathbf {0}$ in W .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The kernel and the image $\operatorname {im} (f)=\{f(\mathbf {v} ):\mathbf {v} \in V\}$ are subspaces of V and W , respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] An important example is the kernel of a linear map $\mathbf {x} \mapsto A\mathbf {x}$ for some fixed matrix A .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The kernel of this map is the subspace of vectors $\mathbf {x}$ such that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {0}$ , which is precisely the set of solutions to the system of homogeneous linear equations belonging to A .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In the corresponding map $f\mapsto D(f)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}a_{i}{\frac {d^{i}f}{dx^{i}}},$ the derivatives of the function f appear linearly (as opposed to $f^{\prime \prime }(x)^{2}$ , for example).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Since differentiation is a linear procedure (that is, $(f+g)^{\prime }=f^{\prime }+g^{\prime }$ and $(c\cdot f)^{\prime }=c\cdot f^{\prime }$ for a constant c ) this assignment is linear, called a linear differential operator.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] In particular, the solutions to the differential equation $D(f)=0$ form a vector space (over **R** or **C**).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The existence of kernels and images is part of the statement that the category of vector spaces (over a fixed field F ) is an abelian category, that is, a corpus of mathematical objects and structure-preserving maps between them (a category) that behaves much like the category of abelian groups.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The *direct product* of vector spaces and the *direct sum* of vector spaces are two ways of combining an indexed family of vector spaces into a new vector space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The *direct product* $\textstyle {\prod _{i\in I}V_{i}}$ of a family of vector spaces $V_{i}$ consists of the set of all tuples $\left(\mathbf {v} _{i}\right)_{i\in I}$ , which specify for each index i in some index set I an element $\mathbf {v} _{i}$ of $V_{i}$ .
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] Addition and scalar multiplication is performed componentwise.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] A variant of this construction is the *direct sum* ${\textstyle \bigoplus _{i\in I}V_{i}}$ (also called coproduct and denoted ${\textstyle \coprod _{i\in I}V_{i}}$ ), where only tuples with finitely many nonzero vectors are allowed.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] If the index set I is finite, the two constructions agree, but in general they are different.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The *tensor product* $V\otimes _{F}W,$ or simply $V\otimes W,$ of two vector spaces V and W is one of the central notions of multilinear algebra, which deals with extending notions such as linear maps to several variables.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p01] The tensor product is a particular vector space that is a *universal* recipient of bilinear maps $g,$ as follows.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] From the point of view of linear algebra, vector spaces are completely understood insofar as any vector space over a given field is characterized, up to isomorphism, by its dimension.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] However, vector spaces *per se* do not offer a framework to deal with the question—crucial to analysis—whether a sequence of functions converges to another function.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Likewise, linear algebra is not adapted to deal with infinite series, since the addition operation allows only finitely many terms to be added.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Therefore, the needs of functional analysis require considering additional structures.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] A vector space may be given a partial order $\,\leq ,\,$ under which some vectors can be compared.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, n -dimensional real space $\mathbf {R} ^{n}$ can be ordered by comparing its vectors componentwise.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Ordered vector spaces, for example Riesz spaces, are fundamental to Lebesgue integration, which relies on the ability to express a function as a difference of two positive functions $f=f^{+}-f^{-}.$ where $f^{+}$ denotes the positive part of f and $f^{-}$ the negative part.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] "Measuring" vectors is done by specifying a norm, a datum which measures lengths of vectors, or by an inner product, which measures angles between vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Norms and inner products are denoted $|\mathbf {v} |$ and $\langle \mathbf {v} ,\mathbf {w} \rangle ,$ respectively.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Convergence questions are treated by considering vector spaces V carrying a compatible topology, a structure that allows one to talk about elements being close to each other.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Compatible here means that addition and scalar multiplication have to be continuous maps.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In such *topological vector spaces* one can consider series of vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The mode of convergence of the series depends on the topology imposed on the function space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In such cases, pointwise convergence and uniform convergence are two prominent examples.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] A way to ensure the existence of limits of certain infinite series is to restrict attention to spaces where any Cauchy sequence has a limit; such a vector space is called complete.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Roughly, a vector space is complete provided that it contains all necessary limits.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, the vector space of polynomials on the unit interval $[0,1],$ equipped with the topology of uniform convergence is not complete because any continuous function on $[0,1]$ can be uniformly approximated by a sequence of polynomials, by the Weierstrass approximation theorem.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In contrast, the space of *all* continuous functions on $[0,1]$ with the same topology is complete.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Their study—a key piece of functional analysis—focuses on infinite-dimensional vector spaces, since all norms on finite-dimensional topological vector spaces give rise to the same notion of convergence.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The image at the right shows the equivalence of the 1 -norm and $\infty$ -norm on $\mathbf {R} ^{2}:$ as the unit "balls" enclose each other, a sequence converges to zero in one norm if and only if it so does in the other norm.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In the infinite-dimensional case, however, there will generally be inequivalent topologies, which makes the study of topological vector spaces richer than that of vector spaces without additional data.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] From a conceptual point of view, all notions related to topological vector spaces should match the topology.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, instead of considering all linear maps (also called functionals) $V\to W,$ maps between topological vector spaces are required to be continuous.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In particular, the (topological) dual space $V^{*}$ consists of continuous functionals $V\to \mathbf {R}$ (or to $\mathbf {C}$ ).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The fundamental Hahn–Banach theorem is concerned with separating subspaces of appropriate topological vector spaces by continuous functionals.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Imposing boundedness conditions not only on the function, but also on its derivatives leads to Sobolev spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Complete inner product spaces are known as *Hilbert spaces*, in honor of David Hilbert.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The Hilbert space $L^{2}(\Omega ),$ with inner product given by $\langle f\ ,\ g\rangle =\int _{\Omega }f(x){\overline {g(x)}}\,dx,$ where ${\overline {g(x)}}$ denotes the complex conjugate of $g(x),$ is a key case.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] By definition, in a Hilbert space, any Cauchy sequence converges to a limit.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Conversely, finding a sequence of functions $f_{n}$ with desirable properties that approximate a given limit function is equally crucial.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Early analysis, in the guise of the Taylor approximation, established an approximation of differentiable functions f by polynomials.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] By the Stone–Weierstrass theorem, every continuous function on $[a,b]$ can be approximated as closely as desired by a polynomial.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] A similar approximation technique by trigonometric functions is commonly called Fourier expansion, and is much applied in engineering.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Such a set of functions is called a *basis* of $H,$ its cardinality is known as the Hilbert space dimension.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Not only does the theorem exhibit suitable basis functions as sufficient for approximation purposes, but also together with the Gram–Schmidt process, it enables one to construct a basis of orthogonal vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Such orthogonal bases are the Hilbert space generalization of the coordinate axes in finite-dimensional Euclidean space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The solutions to various differential equations can be interpreted in terms of Hilbert spaces.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, a great many fields in physics and engineering lead to such equations, and frequently solutions with particular physical properties are used as basis functions, often orthogonal.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] As an example from physics, the time-dependent Schrödinger equation in quantum mechanics describes the change of physical properties in time by means of a partial differential equation, whose solutions are called wavefunctions.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Definite values for physical properties such as energy, or momentum, correspond to eigenvalues of a certain (linear) differential operator and the associated wavefunctions are called eigenstates.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The spectral theorem decomposes a linear compact operator acting on functions in terms of these eigenfunctions and their eigenvalues.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] General vector spaces do not possess a multiplication between vectors.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] A vector space equipped with an additional bilinear operator defining the multiplication of two vectors is an *algebra over a field* (or *F*-algebra if the field *F* is specified).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, the set of all polynomials $p(t)$ forms an algebra known as the polynomial ring: using that the sum of two polynomials is a polynomial, they form a vector space; they form an algebra since the product of two polynomials is again a polynomial.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Rings of polynomials (in several variables) and their quotients form the basis of algebraic geometry, because they are rings of functions of algebraic geometric objects.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Examples include the vector space of n -by- n matrices, with $[x,y]=xy-yx,$ the commutator of two matrices, and $\mathbf {R} ^{3},$ endowed with the cross product.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The tensor algebra $\operatorname {T} (V)$ is a formal way of adding products to any vector space V to obtain an algebra.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] As a vector space, it is spanned by symbols, called simple tensors $\mathbf {v} _{1}\otimes \mathbf {v} _{2}\otimes \cdots \otimes \mathbf {v} _{n},$ where the degree n varies.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The multiplication is given by concatenating such symbols, imposing the distributive law under addition, and requiring that scalar multiplication commute with the tensor product ⊗, much the same way as with the tensor product of two vector spaces introduced in the above section on tensor products.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] A *vector bundle* is a family of vector spaces parametrized continuously by a topological space *X*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] More precisely, a vector bundle over *X* is a topological space *E* equipped with a continuous map $\pi :E\to X$ such that for every *x* in *X*, the fiber π−1(*x*) is a vector space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The case dim *V* = 1 is called a line bundle.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For any vector space *V*, the projection *X* × *V* → *X* makes the product *X* × *V* into a "trivial" vector bundle.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Vector bundles over *X* are required to be locally a product of *X* and some (fixed) vector space *V*: for every *x* in *X*, there is a neighborhood *U* of *x* such that the restriction of π to π−1(*U*) is isomorphic to the trivial bundle *U* × *V* → *U*.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Despite their locally trivial character, vector bundles may (depending on the shape of the underlying space *X*) be "twisted" in the large (that is, the bundle need not be (globally isomorphic to) the trivial bundle *X* × *V*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, the Möbius strip can be seen as a line bundle over the circle *S*1 (by identifying open intervals with the real line).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] It is, however, different from the cylinder *S*1 × **R**, because the latter is orientable whereas the former is not.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Properties of certain vector bundles provide information about the underlying topological space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] For example, the tangent bundle consists of the collection of tangent spaces parametrized by the points of a differentiable manifold.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The tangent bundle of the circle *S*1 is globally isomorphic to *S*1 × **R**, since there is a global nonzero vector field on *S*1.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In contrast, by the hairy ball theorem, there is no (tangent) vector field on the 2-sphere *S*2 which is everywhere nonzero.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] K-theory studies the isomorphism classes of all vector bundles over some topological space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] In addition to deepening topological and geometrical insight, it has purely algebraic consequences, such as the classification of finite-dimensional real division algebras: **R**, **C**, the quaternions **H** and the octonions **O**.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The cotangent bundle of a differentiable manifold consists, at every point of the manifold, of the dual of the tangent space, the cotangent space.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Sections of that bundle are known as differential one-forms.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Roughly, *affine spaces* are vector spaces whose origins are not specified.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] More precisely, an affine space is a set with a free transitive vector space action.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] An important example is the space of solutions of a system of inhomogeneous linear equations $A\mathbf {v} =\mathbf {b}$ generalizing the homogeneous case discussed in the above section on linear equations, which can be found by setting $\mathbf {b} =\mathbf {0}$ in this equation.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The space of solutions is the affine subspace **x** + *V* where **x** is a particular solution of the equation, and *V* is the space of solutions of the homogeneous equation (the nullspace of *A*).
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] The set of one-dimensional subspaces of a fixed finite-dimensional vector space *V* is known as *projective space*; it may be used to formalize the idea of parallel lines intersecting at infinity.
[src:eigen-cpp-lib/vector-space-p02] Grassmannians and flag manifolds generalize this by parametrizing linear subspaces of fixed dimension *k* and flags of subspaces, respectively.
